post_text: Dear Elba Friends and Family ~ Our Elba 7th - 12th graders are starting a Veterans project for school and for Veteran's Day. We are looking for Veterans who would volunteer to be interviewed by our students. We currently have 48 students so we are hoping to find 48 Veterans. The interviews will run from October 10th to October 18th. If you or any one you know is willing to donate their time and experiences or have any other questions about this project, please contact Jennifer Skrdla at the school 308.863.2228. The Elba students, teachers and administrators appreciate your willingness, time and commitment to this worthy and important academic project. Thank you.

post_text:
The February Elementary student of the month is Kassidy Shuda. Kassidy showed excellence in education. Her teacher states: “Kassidy consistently performs well on her homework assignments and on unit tests. She works hard in the classroom to do her very best work. Kassidy takes constructive criticism and uses it to better her writing skills. The essay answers on her last History test were awesome! I appreciate her spunky attitude and enthusiasm in the classroom. She helps spur others on to do their best also. Kassidy is an excellent candidate for Student of the Month because of her academic achievement and her excitement about learning.”
Congrats Kassidy on Elementary student of the month!!

post_text:
The February high school student of the month is Amber Dzingle. Amber showed area of excellence in her Education, character, and her leadership skills. One aspect her teacher saw was in taking a new task head on. The teacher states: “Amber has done a terrific job of taking on a new instrument this year, she has been working so hard to not only figure it out, but be ready to perform for contest. She doesn't give up, she works hard, and she is such a good sport about it all. Music is important to her and it shows every day as she encourages and helps other students and gives her best effort every day in class as well.”
Congrats Amber on student of the month!

post_text:
All students K-6 will be participating in the “Jump Rope for Heart” event. Envelopes were sent home with students on February 10th. Our event will run through February 28th. Everything will be due on March 1st. During these two weeks students will be doing many different activities involving jump ropes.
• All checks must be made out to “American Heart Association”
• Return event envelopes to Mr. Polk by March 1st
• Our goal this year is to raise $500
• Thank you gifts will be awarded to students who participate
This is an Elba Elementary community service event that benefits the American Heart Association and helps promote the importance of being fit in our community. This is a great event for a great cause. If we raise enough money, the Elementary PE program does benefit from donations by receiving a US games gift certificate. Thanks to everyone who will participate and support this great cause! If you have any questions feel free to contact me at school (308-863-2228) or by email: samuel.polk@esu10.org

post_text:
Elem Student of the month: Garrett Wells
One elementary teacher said of Garrett “Every morning he comes in to put his folder on my desk. If the day before we forgotten to pick up our pencils (Sticks with numbers on them) he will do it without even asking. He is always willing to help me out around the classroom, and makes sure the classroom is cleaned up. This to me shows leadership because once he starts doing it, his other classmates will start helping him. He is always willing to help not only me but also his classmates. He is a fun student to have around.”
Garrett has shown leadership characteristics along with strong character.

High school student of the month is Rebecca Fanta. The characteristics her teachers have said she exemplifies are educational and strong successful character traits.

Ms. Skerdla said of Rebecca “When Rebecca is faced with a decision, she contemplates how the decision will affect her school work. She wanted to ensure that she will be successful in school first and then extra-curriculars second.”

Mr. King said of Rebecca “Rebecca has shown many characteristics that demonstrate success. When Rebecca is faced with a decision, she contemplates how the decision will affect her school work.”

Congratulations goes to Rebecca Fanta for her focus on education and her persevering attitude.

post_text: Today between 10:15 to 11:00, we had the Howard County, Valley County and O'Neill K-9 units at our school as part of a drug dog training exercise. As part of this exercise, students and staff were asked to stay in their classroom as to not interfere or distract the dogs. The exercise went very, very well and all the sheriffs involved wanted every one to know how much they appreciated Ebla Public School's time and cooperation.

post_text:
Congratulations to Tamy Morrow for being our Staff Member of the Month for December. An anonymous nomination states "I nominate Tamy Morrow as teacher of the month. I know she doesn't have a piece of paper to declare that she is a qualified teacher but paper or no paper Tamy is a teacher. She teaches us very useful things like work ethic, good cleaning tips, respect, and how to deal with people. She demonstrates a very good work ethic and she doesn't get as much credit as she deserves. Tamy is a great listener and I feel like if I need anything, I can talk to her about it. She cares for me more than any other faculty or staff member. She does a great job keeping the school clean, driving bus,m and being/doing anything else we need her for. Without Tamy this school wouldn't be able to go round! Tamy is truly Wonder Woman!"
Great Job, Tamy!

post_text:
Congratulations to Preston West-Perez for being the November Secondary Student of the Month. He was nominated by Mrs. Burns and she said "Preston has been such a leader this year both in the regular music classroom, as well as with One Act and sports. He tries to lead by example, and inspires fellow students to be eligible, to stay focused, to work together and certainly to do a great job! In sports he has spoken up, reminding students of their responsibilities to each other and to the team, while encouraging all students to do well academically as well as athletically. In One Act, he was the lead crew member, and he made sure all props, costumes, and people were taken care of, making sure on a daily basis that the group was as ready as possible, while always having a good attitude, being willing to go above and beyond and doing so. He is definitely my nomination for student of the month!"
Great job, Preston!
